				 Six killed on road in Midnapore
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Tamluk, Oct. 14: Two mishaps claimed six lives on the same national highway in East Midnapore today.																								Four persons were killed when a matador van carrying flowers rammed into a sand-laden truck at Kolaghat at 1am.																								Police said about a dozen people were taking flowers to sell in Kolaghat. Muktipada Raut, 55, Jugal Giri, 48, Anwar Mullick, 75, from Kharagpur, and Mumtaz Khan, 30, the trucks cleaner, were killed. The driver of the matador is among the eight in hospital.																								I was returning from Kharagpur to Bankra in Howrah with an empty vehicle and gave a lift to them. The truck in front braked suddenly as police stopped it. I could not, said Ustam Khan. 																								Narayan Nayek, the secretary of the state flower growers association, accused the police of taking bribes from trucks on that stretch of NH41. East Midnapore police chief G.A. Srinivas promised a probe.																								At Haldias Brajalalchak, motorcyclist Arup Chakraborty, 22, and pillion rider Mukesh Sahu, 24, fell while negotiating a pothole and were run over by a truck around 4am. 																								Arup, from Guwahati, and Mukesh, of Liluah, worked in Haldia.
